t.\nIs less than one-fourth of the taxes\ncharged by local. State and Federal\ngovernments for the ?.riv'le?e\nowning property and doing business\nand the protection of the ?\"d\nIt repreaents a profit of almost exactly\n1 per cent on the gross bu*4\"\nness done during the year when the\nrailroads hsndled more ,ret*ht\npassengers tbsn ever before in their\nhistory.\nf Strtktac Illastrattaa.\n\"Tllese figures strikingly \",u**\nMrate the importance to the railroads\nof the relief to be afforded\nbv <he Wlnslow bill, which authorises\npartial payments pending\naettlement of the guaranty provided\nfor by the transportation act for\nthe six months following the termination\nof Federal control, which\nhas just been signed by the President.\nWithout the guaranty most\nof the railroads would have been\nbankrupt several months ago. particularly\nas the entire net operating\nttcome of $*3,000,000 was earned by\n0B]y about half of the Class T raitToads.\nthe other half having deficits\nfar the year.\nBase Advaaee Applications.\n\"With the promise of the guarsnty\nand with the assistance of\nabout 8182.000.000 actually advanced\non applications filed prior to September\n1. the roads have struggled\nalong for a year, but It took a new\nlaw passed a year after the passage\nof the transportation act to make\nany of tha balance available, and\nthe relief could not have been delayed\nmuch longer without disastrous\nresults. The total guaranty\nfor the six months' period is estimated\nst about *600.000,000, of\nwhich about 8200.000.000 has already\nbeen paid out for back wages\n?under the Railroad Labor Board\n^award of July 20. In addition the\nrailroads racetved about *160.000,000\nfor their guaranty for January and\nFebruary, 1*20. when they were\nstill under Federal control.\n\"While tha taxpayers are grumbling\nabout paying the guaranty,\nthey might passe to' remember that\nthe railroads themselves have tq\npay nearly Malf of it for their\ntaxea.\"\nDAY FAIRLY LARGE\nIN CURB MARKET\nTrading Assumes Moderate\nProportions and Movements\nAre Mixed and Wide.\nNEW YORK. March 4.?Trading\nin the curb market today assumed\nmoderately large proportions at\ntimes, and movements In some\nI Issues were mixed and wide. The\n.opening was quiet, and it waa sevFeral\nminutes before sales were recorded\nIn some of the usually active\nStocks Purlng tha afternoon prlcea\nHnoved within a narrow range and\n1 business quieted down somewhat.\nOne of the early features was\ntha sharp rise in Maracatbo Oil to\nabove It. Carlb Syndicate waa\nweak. Ouffey Gillespie was offered\ndown rapidly, and in a few minutes\nshowed a loss of points.\nDurant Motors changed hands\naround Its recent high. In the metal\n-roup a somewhat firmer tone waa\naoticeabl*. Boston Montana selling\nat its highest level of the week,\nhiere were several exceptionally\nweak spots In the bonr section.\nJUTW YORK PRODUCE.\nXEW TORK. March 4.?Butter\ntnlrket quieter. Creamery extras.\ncreamery firsts. 48s5?c:\nrean-ery. higher scoring. MH*\nI me; State dairy tubs. 2*a52c:\nImitation creamery firsts. 27a!8c.\nCheese market firm. State, whole\nnllk specials. ISHaiic: whole milk\nancy 24tta2tHe; whole milk\nl,,wer grades. Ual4c: Wisconsin\nLhole nllk. fancy Toung Americas.\n7a2*c: Stats, skims, specials. 17 H\nIII*4c: skims, choiee. llsltc; skims,\nsir to good, l?al2c; skims, lower\nLriufcs. ia?c.\nr Eggs Market unsettled. nesrby\nwhite fsncy. 47a4*c: naarby brown\nFancy. 4*a<lc;- extra, J8aJS*c;j\nnils. ?4*aJ<c. i\nAUTOMOBILE RE(\nSHOWS\nNo Permanent Recovery\nion?Export Trade\n<Tk? WasblBfton Hei\nPreliminary figures indicate that\nthe totai number of motor cars, s\nIncluding passenger cara and i\ntrucks, registered in the United\nStates in 19St amounted tp t.275.- t\n000. This number may be\" com- J\npared with approximately 7.MM0*\ncara registered in 191S, showtyig an J\nincrease for the year of about K- 1\n715.000 Thfa largest previous Rain 1\nin registration for any single year J\nwas tn 19IS when the total increase\nwas about 1,435.000 cars. Thus in 1\nspite of the sev^-e depression under\nwhich the automobile industry C\nhas been laboring in recent ninths\nthere was very large production\nand sale of cars to the publio last v\nyear. It\nThe effect of the business depres- Jj\nsjion on the automobile industry Is\nbest shown perhapa by the figures\ncollected In the recent United States\nindustrial employment survey -con-\nducted by the Department of Labor. 1\nOn January 1, *1921. the total num- J\nber of employes in the automobile\nindustry was only 31 per cent of\nthe number employed in January\nof the previous year. Press reports f\nhave indicated /that better condi-\ntiona were appearing in the in-\ndustry in recent weeks, but it is a\nquestion whether this is not due\nto seasonal conditions rather than s\nto any permanent improvement.\nThe Department of Labor's report\non employment in selected Indus- f\ntries for February shows an in- i\ncrease of 2.5 per cent in the number\nof employes in the automobile\nindustry during the past month, but\nthe number is still only 36 per cent\nof the men employed a year ago. j\nGeneral business has not yet r\nreached a point which would favor\nany permanent improvement in the\nmotor industry. Notwithstanding J\ncertain arguments to the contrary, j\nautomobiles must be placed in the\nclass of luxuries. In any period of 8\nbusiness depression these commodi- C\nties are the ones which are likely J\nto suffer most. Farmers, who have E\nbeen large purchasers of automobiles\nin recent years, are suffering 1\nseverely from the decline in the i\nprices of farm products. In many\ninstances the prices received for\ntheir products this year will not pay J\nthe cost of production, consequently\nthey will not anrcha*e many auto- I\nmobiles. The depression in other 1\nindustries has caused the large prof-\nits of a year ago to shrink very 1\nmaterially. Under these conditions\nit Is impossible to expect any rapid\nimprovement in the automobile ia-\ndustry.\nFAVORS ORDER TO\nAID HOME SEEKERSI:\nI 1\nI 1\nWestern Canadian Prospective\nCitizens Greatly Benefit\nBy Recent Ruling. i\nI\nOTTAWA. Ont., March 4.?Settlers fl\nseeking homes in Western Canada\nwill be materially benefited by an! f\norder-in-council just approved which g\nterminates on May 1 the plan by\nwhich all government lands within\nfifteen miles of railway* were with- t\ndrawn from homestead and pre-\nemption rights and reserved entirely\nfor soldier settlement. a\nThis reservation, however, will f\nstill apply to lands withdrawn for\nsoldier settlement in the Porcupine 1\nForest Reserve, the Riding Moun- i\ntain Reserve, the Hudson Bay 1\nCompany and the Doukhobor settle- i\nments. These will remain as areas T\nfor settlement by soldier farmers, c\nPower is also reserved by the gov- ?a\nernment to withdraw for soldier\nsettlement any other areas if nec- c\nessary to give a farm home to ?verv-\none of Canada's former soldiers who\ndesires to go upon the land. 8\nFollowing Reported Policy. t\nIn reserving all lands within\nfifteen miles of transportation lines.\nCanada was following out its an- f\nnounced policy that the men who e\nfought the nation's battles should c\nhave tho best land within the power p\nof the nation to bestow. There are g\nstill vast areas of land in Canada\nfar removed from railways that are f\nopen to homesteading. but most of v\nthe settlers who are pouring inio the\ncountry now are buying farms near g\nthe railways either from the rail- f\nways themselves, land companies or\nprivate owners. f\nThe new order in council means\nthat some of the best agricultural\nland In Canada will be thrown open\nfor free settlement and it is believed\nit will have the effect of Inrreasing\nthe influx of homeseekers. The four\nprovinces affected are the Manitoba.\nSaskatchewan. Alberta and British\nColumbia. Q\nCOTTONSEED OIL.\n\nNEW TORK. March 4.?Cotton- f\n!Hd oil waa steady. Spot, 0.85-7.SO; c\ncrude. S.25 aalei. Fu