stock in\nlevators. 1,291.070 bus. Cob corn\na Arm at $4a4.10 bid for car lots ol\n>rime yellow on spot. Track yelow\ncorn. No. 2 or 3. for domestic\nlellvery. is quotable at 86c per bu\nThe market was firm early in the\nlay. and at noon contract spot held\nit itMc per bu.\nA cargo of 3.210 bus No. 3 white\norn sold at 82>4c per bu. car of\nJo. 3 white spot sold at &2\\c.\nClosing prices: Contract tpot\n3*iy; March. 83lie.\nTrack yellow corn was firmer at\nhe *10*0 at 87c and cob corn was\nligher at $4.15 to $4.25 per bb?.\nOats?Receipts. nil; shipments\nrom elevators. 7.400 bu.; stock in\nlevators. 518.930 bu.; No. 2 white\nats were steady during the foreloon\nat 52a52%c for No. 2 white\nnd 51c for No. 2 white.\nMarket closed firmer at 53Via54r\nor No. 2 and 52a52%c for No. 3\nrhlte oats.\nRye?Receipts. 57,179 bu: stock In\nlevators, 708,674 bu.; shipments\nrom elevators. 41.291 bu.: market\nras quiet, but' firmer, and around\nnidday No. 2 Western spot was\n[Uoted at $1.70 per bu.\nSales Included 900 bu. No. 2 Westrn\nspot. $1.69: car No. 2 Westrn\nspot was quoted at $1.70 per bu,\nJJo. 2 Western spot closed at $1,711\n>er bu.\nHay?Receipts. 22 tons. We quote:\nlo. 2 timothy. $24a24.50: No. 3 tlmthy,\n$16.50a21; No. 1 lieht clover\nnixed. $22a22.50. No. 2 light clover\nnixed $18a21; No. clover jnlxed.\n20a21; No. 2 clover mixed. V16al9:\nJo. 3 olover mixed. lllalS; No. 1\nlover. $21.50a24.50; No. 2 clover,\n16.50a20; No. 3 clover. $111116;\nample hay. $10al5.\nA\nWASHINGTON\nManaged Corporation\nCltlaena of the National Capital\nare offered a special opportunity\nto Invest in a new and\ngrowing Commercial Banking\nInstitution, now paying dividends,\nand which on Its record\npromises a high earning power.\nThe business of this institution.\nthe INTERNATIONAL FINANCE\nCORPORATION. Is directed\nby some of- Washington's\nmost conservative and leading\nmen. Among the officer* and directors\nare such men as:\nJ. A. a. Adair P. W. MeKeasle\nw. 1.. Batekelar C. M. Pepper\nW. W. Carter Ben k Prlae*\nC. A. Dasxlsi Kiwrfr* I- Htaek\nDak* W. R. Tarkeraaaa\ntrltsr C. I.aaape Ma R. Waller\nI. Whltlac Kate*.\nA booklet containing full information\nwill be sent to you on\nrequest.\nE. L Stack 4 Co.\nInvestment Seemrttle*\nMain 736. 734 Fifteenth St\n\nFAITH IN HARDING\nAND REVIVED HOPE\nAIDS GRAIN TRADE\nConstructive Move Starts\nAs Friendly Feeling\nHits Market.\nDIP IS MADE EARLY\nGreen Bug Reports Received\nFrom the Southwest\nHelp Prices.\nCHICAGO, March 4.?A feeling in\ntrade circle* that the new administration.\nunder the guidance of\n(President Harding, will not Inter,\nfere with business and that condit\ntions should steadily grow better\nIn all trade lines was the basis for\na more friendly feeling to the con-\natructive side.\nThere were also other contributing\nfactors, the chief of which\n1 was an increased number of bug\nreports- Selling pressure was restrlcted.\nas the average trader 1*\nunable to see the way clearly and\nprices responded readily to fair\n1 buying. A dip was made early on\nselling due to the President's veto\n1 of the emergency tariff bill which\nwas followed by a bulge and closed\nat around the beet prices. At the\nfinish wheat was 1% to Hi cents\nhigher, with March leading. Corn\nwas up Vt to cent, oats S to\ncent, rye tt to 114 cent, and barley j\ncent.\n1 Green Bac Rep?rt?.\nGreen bug report# from Okla?\nhoma were numeroui and claimed\ndamage to the wheat crop In some\ninstances, while others said there j\nI van none. The Modern Miller re-\nported no damage and gave an ?ni\ncouraging showing of the crop.\nSome of the green bug reports were\nbacked by buying orders which\nwith buying based on reports of\n250.000 bushels sold at the gulf for\nexport at 14 cents over March, and\nof 160,000 bushels Manitoba sold at\nthe seaboard, were bull helps. There j\nwere claims of Hessian fly and\nchinch bugs, the latter from Mis* l\nsouri, and of high and dry winds\ndamaging the crop in Kansas. I\nCorn went to a new high for the\nI present upturn, 72cents for May\nwith the finish at V* cent under the^ l\ntop. Strength in wheat, talk of re- j\nduced receipts, and good export\nbuying were the main factors in\nmaking stronger market. Report j\nsales were 400,000 bushels here and\n250,000 bushels at the seaboard, al*\nthough the latter was probably a J\n1 duplicate of the Chicago business. 3\nCountry offerings were lighter al- j\nthough arrivals here continue lib-\ni eral, 468 cars. Cash prices were t\nI 4 to IS cent higher with domestic\nsales 40,000 bushels.\nOats Take Jump.\n1 Heavy buying to cover May oats\nfor a large local operator waa the\nmain life to that market. Prices I\nadvanced cent to 46 34 cents and I\nclosed to hi cent from the top. 1\nThe ease with which the oats were\nsecured from local traders sur- i\nprised them. Shipping sales were j\n75,000 bushels and receipts 120,000 1\nbushels.\nNew York sold a cargo of rye for\nexport late Thursday and was in i\nthe market for May here today. 1\nOfferings were light and prices ad- I\nvanced l*i cent. Exports from\nJuly 1, 1920. to February 28, 1921. I\nwere 29.298.000 bushels.\nFollow in* are tod*?'* quotations on grata i\nand proYisions:\nWheat? Open. HlfU. Ixiw. Ck**.\nMarch 1.70 1.74 1.70 1.73*4\nMay 1.02% 1.04. 1 61% IM\\\nCorn? 1\nMay 71% .72'* .71 .71% I\nJuly 73% .74*4 .73 .73*\nOats? J\nMay 46?; 4H\\ .43% .46??\nJuly 47 .47?* .47 .47%\nP*tkMar\n22 10 22 23 21.00 1T2.30 f\ni Lard?\nMay 12.32 12.3.\" 12.27 13 30\n(Furnished by V. B. Hibbs A Co.. Members\n1 Chicago Board of Trado.) c\n423.193 Surplus Freight Cars.\nThe surplus of freight cars on the\nrailroads, of the United States\nreached 423.193 durinK the week of\nFebruary 23. and is rapidly ap-\nproachinp the surplus which j\nmarked the period following the\narmistice, the car service division of\nthe American Railway Association\nannounced today. The surplus for\nt the week previous was 5*2.530.\nSTATEMENT OF THE\nLIFE AND CASUA\nCOMP.\nOf Nashville, Tcnn.. on the 3