e o\nTransactions Would Impair\nReliability of Quotations.\nCHICAGO. War. 4.?Warning I\nproducers against destruction of tli\nnation's grain marketing machiner\nby enactment of class legislatk\nor formation of powerful farm*\ngroups or control of prices is cot\n1 tained fn the February business n\nview bulletin of the National Cil\n1 Bank, of New York.\n1 The speculator, according to tt\nreview, performs an extremely u?<\nful task by carrying the crops froi\nthe* time they leave the produce\n1 until they reach the consumer. \"An\nwhoever carries products for a fi\nture market is taking risks, an\n1 therefore must be classed as a spe<\nulator,\" :t says.\ni The truth is that the Chicag\nmarket is the chief hedging ma:\ni ket for dealers and millers ov?\n1 the world. Trading there is n\nlatfd to the grain and flour businef\n1 of the world, and not merely to\ni crops of this country. The market\nfluctuate, as we have seen, becaui\nconditions are always changini\nand sellers, as well ax buyers; farn\ners. as well as traders, are quic\nto want price changes if conditioi\nt change in their favor.\n1 \"It is better to have a fluctuai\ning market than no market at al\nSome of the most bitter complainl\nin recent months have alleged thi\nf farmers could not get a bid f<\ntheir products. There have bee\ntimes In the last six month* whe\n1 wool-grower# have said there wa\nno market for their products.\"\nPresent Market Protects.\nThe present broad, open grai\nr market is a protection to the farn\ni er. according to the review, and r<\nstrictions in volume of transactor\nf would \"destroy or limit the us<\nk fulness of market place* and in\npair the reliability of the market\nAs a matter of fact, commodity\ntraded in upon the exchanges ha>\nfallen no faster or farther tha\nthose not traded In. but have fare\ncuite an well, or better, as wiuvei\ncomparisons with wool, rubber, coj\nper. rice and livestock.\nJ \"The proposal to control the pr?\nduction and marketing of far:\nproducts so that a farmer will kno\nwhen he plants his crop what 1\nwill get for it. and always be a:\nsured of a fair profit, will be ai\ntended by very great difficulties,\ninvolves disconnecting markets an\nI prices in the United States froi\nmarkets and prices in other cour\ntries, which would mean the dis\ncontinuance of agricultural expoi\nor imports or else includes the tas\nof stabilising prices all over t*\n1 world.\"\nAfter referring further to pric?\nfixing proposals, the review declar<\nthat such plans seem to develo\nlogically into guild socialism.*'\ncashgrain market.\nCH1CAOO. March 4.?Wheat: rt<\nj *'ntfr. relatively lr lower: oth<\nunchanged Shipping sale,, K 0<\nJ bushels. Tra.k Chicago: No\ndark Northern. J1 ?5: No. dar\nNorthern. 11.83.\nCorn: Steady to higher. Shi|\npine sales. Sio.000 bushels. Trac\nChicago: Sample crade. 55c; No.\nmixed. ?lc; No. 5 mixed. CZ'-jafiSU.\nNo. 4 mixed. SJHaS4c: Net\nmixed, fifi'.itflc.p: Vo. 2 mixe\n1 08*ic: No. yellow. ?la61^*c: No.\nyellow. s;>,a?3'ie: No. 4 yelloi\n?J'4 act ijr: No 3 yellow. ?5',a?T\nNo. yellow. iH'jc: No. 4 whit\n1 C3'xaC4e^: No. 3 white. No.\nwhite. 6Sc; No. 1 white old. 71e.\nOats: Steady to So up. Shippir\nsales. 75.00ft bushels. Track Ch\nCairo: No. 4 white. 4IHc; No\nwhite. 4Sa45*ic.\nSimp\nB\nSwartze\ni\ni\nYour unit\nno adjusting, no\ni have chosen yoi\nterest on each p\nYou have only\ninvestment.\nWe would like\nmore fully.\nI\nSWAI\nIV\nCommencing M\ni\nPit Iron Production UKUt TStS JS\nSlum,UyeDtdmt JZ. Cft'\n.?r?? ?~?ssrsi sa.'STo.^r^;\n1J37.267 tou, the Iow?t monthly m furnaces la blast.\nI output ia (Is years with the eicep\ntioa of October, lilt, a month la METAJ, MARKET.\nwhich production was curtailed by\nthe steel strike, la January, pro- NEW TORK. March 4.?Handy\nductlon was 2.405.846 tona. and In and Hariran quote bar atlvar. 4p-\\\nFebruary. 1126. 2.07M7S tona. Dally raeatic ft He., unchanged; foreign\nrate during February. It21. was M*c.. off l%c., a new low reoord\n1S7 tons com